<subSubSection id="C3776556EE443B20FC9AFC9BFA4FFC53" pageId="277" pageNumber="278" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEE443B20FC9AFC9BFA4FFC53" blockId="277.[810,1452,173,914]" pageId="277" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE443B20FC9AFC9BFC25FCAE" bold="true" box="[863,992,853,879]" pageId="277" pageNumber="278">Etymology</emphasis>
. The generic name is an anagram of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE443B20FCEFFCB9FC6FFC50" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[810,938,887,913]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Bonnierilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="277" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE443B20FCEFFCB9FC6FFC50" box="[810,938,887,913]" italics="true" pageId="277" pageNumber="278">Bonnierilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is closely related to the new genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556EE443B23FC9AF8BAFDE8FD26" lastPageId="278" lastPageNumber="279" pageId="277" pageNumber="278" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEE443B23FC9AF8BAFDA4FDDA" blockId="277.[810,1452,1907,2070]" lastBlockId="278.[136,778,173,743]" lastPageId="278" lastPageNumber="279" pageId="277" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE443B20FC9AF8BAFC0FF84F" bold="true" box="[863,970,1908,1934]" pageId="277" pageNumber="278">Remarks</emphasis>
. The new genus is similarto 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE443B20FAC3F8BDFA47F84C" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[1286,1410,1907,1933]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Bonnierilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="277" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE443B20FAC3F8BDFA47F84C" box="[1286,1410,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="277" pageNumber="278">Bonnierilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in the following character states: (1) the metasome usually has 2 pairs of defined epimera; (2) the compound distal endopodal segment of the antenna is stout and is not distinctly longer than the first endopodal segment; (3) the second endopodal segment of the mandible is armed with less than 8 setae; (4) the third endopodal segment of the maxilla has only 2 setae; (5) the maxilliped is 1-segmented, without a distal prolongation, and is armed with 1 apical seta; (6) the exopods of legs 2–4 have setae as outer armature elements; (7) the first exopodal segment of leg 4 lacks an inner seta; and (8) the left and right legs of leg pairs 2-4 are usually asymmetrical (
<tableCitation id="C6EF0366EE473B23FDDEFE55FDB4FE77" box="[539,625,411,438]" captionStart="TABLE 5" captionStartId="277.[810,902,957,981]" captionTargetPageId="277" captionText="TABLE 5. Differences between Bonnierilla and Nobinerilla gen. nov." pageId="278" pageNumber="279">Table 5</tableCitation>
). In addition, the third endopodal segment of leg 1 is armed with 5 setae in the new genus, but a few species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE473B23FDE7FE11FD5AFE38" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[546,671,479,505]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Bonnierilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE473B23FDE7FE11FD5AFE38" box="[546,671,479,505]" italics="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">Bonnierilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also have 5 setae rather than the more typical 6 setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEE473B23FF78FDEDFDE8FD26" blockId="278.[136,778,173,743]" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">
Two species currently placed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE473B23FD9FFDEDFD1FFDFC" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[602,730,547,573]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Bonnierilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE473B23FD9FFDEDFD1FFDFC" box="[602,730,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">Bonnierilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE473B23FD37FDEAFEA1FD9E" authority="Stock, 1967" authorityName="Stock" authorityYear="1967" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Nobinerilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE473B23FD37FDEAFCC6FDFC" box="[754,771,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE473B23FF4DFD8BFF09FD9E" box="[136,204,581,607]" italics="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">filipes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEE473B23FF1CFD8BFEA1FD9E" author="Stock, J. H." box="[217,356,581,607]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Sea Fisheries Research Station, Israel, 46 (Reports" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" pagination="1 - 126" part="27" refId="ref331068" refString="Stock, J. H. (1967) Report on the Notodelphyidae (Copepoda, Cyclopoida) of the Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Bulletin of the Sea Fisheries Research Station, Israel, 46 (Reports 27), 1 - 126." title="Report on the Notodelphyidae (Copepoda, Cyclopoida) of the Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Israel South Red Sea Expedition" type="journal article" year="1967">Stock, 1967</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE473B23FE61FD88FCC3FD9E" authority="Schellenberg, 1922" authorityName="Schellenberg" authorityYear="1922" box="[420,774,581,607]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Bonnierilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armata">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE473B23FE61FD88FDDFFD9E" box="[420,538,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">B. armata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEE473B23FDE3FD8BFCC3FD9E" author="Schellenberg, A." box="[550,774,581,607]" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" pagination="217 - 274" part="10" refId="ref330676" refString="Schellenberg, A. (1922) Neue Notodelphyiden des Berliner und Hamburger Museums mit einer Uberscht der ascidienwohnenden Gattungen und Arten. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin, 10 (2), 217 - 274. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / mmnz. 4830100201" title="Neue Notodelphyiden des Berliner und Hamburger Museums mit einer Uberscht der ascidienwohnenden Gattungen und Arten" type="journal article" year="1922">Schellenberg, 1922</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, are recognized as belonging to the new genus and are formally transferred below. Speciesof 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE473B23FD88FD47FD0BFD62" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[589,718,649,675]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Nobinerilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE473B23FD88FD47FD0BFD62" box="[589,718,649,675]" italics="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">Nobinerilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE473B23FD1CFD47FF7CFD04" bold="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4EE473B23FD1CFD47FF7CFD04" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
usually live in colonial ascidians whereas species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE473B23FF4DFD03FECDFD26" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[136,264,717,743]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Bonnierilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="278" pageNumber="279" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE473B23FF4DFD03FECDFD26" box="[136,264,717,743]" italics="true" pageId="278" pageNumber="279">Bonnierilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabit solitary ascidians.
</paragraph>
